TEXT(beginproblem());

Context("Numeric");

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$k = random(2,9,1);
$sin = "x/sqrt($k^2+x^2)";
$cos = "$k/sqrt($k^2 +x^2)";
$sqr = $k**2;

BEGIN_TEXT
Suppose \( \displaystyle x = $k \tan( \theta ) \) and the angle \( \theta \) is in the first quadrant.
Write algebraic expressions for \( \sin( \theta ) \) and \( \cos( \theta ) \) in terms of \( x \). 
$BR
$BR
(a)  \( \sin( \theta ) \) = \{ ans_rule(35) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("formulas") \} 
$BR
$BR
(b)  \( \cos( \theta ) \) = \{ ans_rule(35) \} 
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("formulas") \}
END_TEXT

ANS( Compute("$sin")->cmp() );
ANS( Compute("$cos")->cmp() );

#ANS( fun_cmp( $sin,vars=>'x') );
#ANS( fun_cmp( $cos,vars=>'x' ) );

SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$BR $SPACE $BR 
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$BR 
a) Using the Pythagorean Identity \( \sin^2{ ( \theta )} + \cos^2{ ( \theta ) } =1 \), we know \( \cos{ (\theta) } = \sqrt{1-\sin^2{(\theta)}} \).  We can substitute this identity into the given formula $SPACE $SPACE \( x = $k \tan{(\theta)} = $k \frac{\sin{(\theta)}}{\cos{(\theta)}} = $k \frac{\sin{(\theta)}}{\sqrt{1-\sin^2{(\theta)}}} \) and solve for \( \sin{(\theta)} \) as follows:
$BR $SPACE $BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE \( x \sqrt{1-\sin^2{(\theta)}} = $k \sin{ (\theta )} \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE \( x^2 ( 1 - \sin^2{ (\theta) } = $sqr \sin^2{(\theta)} \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE \( x^2 = \left( $sqr +x^2 \right) \sin^2{(\theta)} \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE \( \sin^2{(\theta)} = \frac{x^2}{$sqr+x^2} \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
$SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE $SPACE \( \sin{(\theta)} = \pm \frac{x}{\sqrt{$sqr+x^2}} \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
Since the angle \( \theta \) is in the first quadrant, \( \sin{ ( \theta ) } \ge 0 \), so \( \sin{ ( \theta ) } = \frac{x}{\sqrt{$sqr+x^2}}  \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
b) \( x = $k \tan{ (  \theta ) } = $k \frac{ \sin{ ( \theta )}}{\cos{ ( \theta )}} = \frac{\frac{$k x}{\sqrt{$sqr+x^2}}}{\cos{(\theta)} } \)
$BR $SPACE $BR
Therefore $SPACE $SPACE \( \cos{(\theta)} = \frac{\frac{$k x}{\sqrt{$sqr+x^2}}}{x} = \frac{$k}{\sqrt{$sqr+x^2}} \)
$BR
END_SOLUTION


